[log] bash[68] stdout ## API Usage Guide
[log] bash[68] stdout ### Core API
[log] bash[68] stdout #### 1. Module Import
[log] bash[68] stdout ```python
[log] bash[68] stdout import arguably
[log] bash[68] stdout from arguably import (
[log] bash[68] stdout     MANUAL, Permissions, PermissionsAlt, HiBye,
[log] bash[68] stdout     get_and_clear_io, run_cli_and_manual,
[log] bash[68] stdout     run_cli_and_manual_main, append_argv
[log] bash[68] stdout )
[log] bash[68] stdout ```
[log] bash[68] stdout #### 2. command() Decorator - Command Definition
[log] bash[68] stdout **Function**: Convert an ordinary function into a command-line command, automatically handling parameter parsing and type conversion.
[log] bash[68] stdout **Decorator Signature**:
[log] bash[68] stdout ```python
[log] bash[68] stdout def command(
[log] bash[68] stdout     func: Optional[Callable] = None,
[log] bash[68] stdout     /,
[log] bash[68] stdout     *,
[log] bash[68] stdout     # Arguments below are passed through to `CommandDecoratorInfo`
[log] bash[68] stdout     alias: Optional[str] = None,
[log] bash[68] stdout     help: bool = True,
[log] bash[68] stdout ) -> Callable:
[log] bash[68] stdout     """
[log] bash[68] stdout     Mark a function as a command that should appear on the CLI. If multiple functions are decorated with this, they will
[log] bash[68] stdout     all be available as subcommands. If only one function is decorated, it is automatically selected - no need to
[log] bash[68] stdout     specify it on the CLI.
[log] bash[68] stdout     Args:
[log] bash[68] stdout         func: The target function.
[log] bash[68] stdout         alias: An alias for this function. For example, `@arguably.command(alias="h")` would alias `h` to the function
[log] bash[68] stdout             that follows.
[log] bash[68] stdout         help: If `False`, the help flag `-h/--help` will not automatically be added to this function.
[log] bash[68] stdout     Returns:
[log] bash[68] stdout         If called with parens `@arguably.command(...)`, returns the decorated function. If called without parens
[log] bash[68] stdout             `@arguably.command`, returns the function `wrap(func_)`, which returns `func_`.
[log] bash[68] stdout     """
[log] bash[68] stdout     def wrap(func_: Callable) -> Callable:
[log] bash[68] stdout         context.add_command(function=func_, alias=alias, help=help)
[log] bash[68] stdout         return func_
[log] bash[68] stdout     # Handle being called as either @arguably.command or @arguably.command()
[log] bash[68] stdout     # We have type: ignore due to https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/10740
[log] bash[68] stdout     return wrap if func is None else wrap(func)  # type: ignore[return-value]
[log] bash[68] stdout ```
[log] bash[68] stdout **Parameter Description**:
[log] bash[68] stdout - `func` (Optional[Callable]): The function to be decorated, usually passed automatically through the decorator syntax.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `alias` (Optional[str]): The alias of the command, used for subcommand access.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `help` (bool): Whether to automatically generate help information, default is True.
[log] bash[68] stdout **Returns**: The decorated function or the function `wrap(func_)`, which returns `func_`.
[log] bash[68] stdout #### 3. run() Function - Application Startup
[log] bash[68] stdout **Function**: Start the command-line application, handling parameter parsing and command execution.
[log] bash[68] stdout **Function Signature**:
[log] bash[68] stdout ```python
[log] bash[68] stdout def run(
[log] bash[68] stdout     name: Optional[str] = None,
[log] bash[68] stdout     always_subcommand: bool = False,
[log] bash[68] stdout     version_flag: Union[bool, Tuple[str], Tuple[str, str]] = False,
[log] bash[68] stdout     strict: bool = True,
[log] bash[68] stdout     show_defaults: bool = True,
[log] bash[68] stdout     show_types: bool = True,
[log] bash[68] stdout     max_description_offset: int = 60,
[log] bash[68] stdout     max_width: int = 120,
[log] bash[68] stdout     command_metavar: str = "command",
[log] bash[68] stdout     output: Optional[TextIO] = None,
[log] bash[68] stdout ) -> Any:
[log] bash[68] stdout ```
[log] bash[68] stdout **Parameter Description**:
[log] bash[68] stdout - `name` (Optional[str]): The name of the application, default is the script file name.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `always_subcommand` (bool): Whether to force the use of the subcommand mode, default is False.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `version_flag` (Union[bool, Tuple[str], Tuple[str, str]]): Configuration of the version flag.
[log] bash[68] stdout   - `True`: Use the default `--version` flag.
[log] bash[68] stdout   - `("-V", "--ver")`: Customize the version flag.
[log] bash[68] stdout   - `False`: Disable the version flag.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `strict` (bool): Whether to use the strict mode, default is True.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `show_defaults` (bool): Whether to display default values in the help information, default is True.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `show_types` (bool): Whether to display parameter types in the help information, default is True.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `max_description_offset` (int): The maximum offset of the description text, default is 60.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `max_width` (int): The maximum width of the output text, default is 120.
[log] bash[68] stdout - `command_metavar` (str): The metavariable name of the subcommand, default is "command".
[log] bash[68] stdout - `output` (Optional[TextIO]): The output stream, default is None (use standard output).
[log] bash[68] stdout **Returns**: The return value of the called command.
[log] bash[68] stdout #### 4. subtype() Decorator - Subtype Definition
